Patch Set 3:

Each time you navigate to or refresh the event logs page, two calls are being made to get the event logs.

https://localhost:8000/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries?$top=1
https://localhost:8000/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries?$top=1000&$skip=0

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> Each time you navigate to or refresh the event logs page, two calls are being made to get the event logs.
> 
> https://localhost:8000/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries?$top=1
> https://localhost:8000/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries?$top=1000&$skip=0

That is correct. The logic behind is as follows:
1. call api to get total rows count (fast call for 1 row, that is why we have $top=1 in query string)
2. calculate query string params and number of calls
3. call api 

At point 2 logic produces second api call, that you mentioned (total count is less that 1000). If there would be more than 1000 rows, let`s say 1500, we would have following calls:
https://localhost:8000/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries?$top=1
https://localhost:8000/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries?$top=1000&$skip=0
https://localhost:8000/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries?$top=1000&$skip=1000

second and third calls are performed simultaneously. On my computer it takes about 4 seconds to get 1000 rows, so if I would have made calls one by one it would take about 8 seconds. Current logic reduces this time to about 4.5 second.

This issue here seems to be a bug in our backend. Based on the Redfish spec, we should support the query parameters that you are sending but that is not the case. We are getting all records when making the first call with the $top=1 parameter.

http://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/DSP0266_1.11.0.html

7.3. Query parameters

To paginate, retrieve subsets of resources, or expand the results in a single response, clients can include the query parameters. Some query parameters apply only to resource collections.

Services:

    Shall only support query parameters on GET operations.
    --> Should support the $top, $skip, only, and excerpt query parameters. <--
    May support the $expand, $filter, and $select query parameters.
    Shall include the ProtocolFeaturesSupported object in the Service Root, if the service supports query parameters.
        This object indicates which parameters and options have been implemented.
    Shall ignore unknown or unsupported query parameters that do not begin with $.
    Shall use the & operator to separate multiple query parameters in a single request.

A 1000 still seems really high? 
You are putting a 1000 on the page?

We load all the entries and then the boostrap-vue table filters, sorts, and paginates the records. They can only get 1000 at a time and it is possible that some systems have many more than that. This was discussed two GUI work groups ago.

Can you mention you are relying on the limited query parameters in bmcweb? 
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/redfish-core/lib/log_services.hpp#L1160
Could you be more specific what should I do, please. I just joined the webui community.
Is this in bmcweb today?

Thanks for the commit! 
Could you use your full name here. From https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#formatting-commit-messages

All commit messages must include a "Signed-off-by" line, which indicates that you the contributor have agreed to the Developer Certificate of Origin (see below). This line must include the full name you commonly use, often a given name and a family name or surname. (ok: Sam Samuelsson, Robert A. Heinlein; not ok: xXthorXx, Sam, RAH)
Done
Any thought on placing the cancel tokens in eventlogs state? This seems to break the paradigm by storing and mutating this data outside state, especially when events are stored there.

Initially I though that cancel token is not part of application state, but now I think that it is. My intention here was to cancel logs request when we change the page from overview to health/event logs and request did not finished yet. I will change it and use store as you suggest.
Ack

Isn't this the eventsPerPage? Can you name be such? 
eventLogsPerPage?
This name could be confusing as this parameter in fact means how much entries we fetch from the api. This has nothing to do with paging on UI.

Can you add some more here? About the query parameters, the number of calls, etc.
We discussed at the GUI workgroup meeting, doing an initial call to fetch atleast a page full (20-1000) then getting the rest in the background (i.e. a lazy load).

We can do that, but we need to think how UI should behave:
1. Pager - now, if we fetch 20 items, pager will show one page and update when more items will be downloaded. We can build pager and show all pages (we know how many items we will get), but then we need to handle scenario when user clicks on the page that we do not have. 
2. Data filters (search etc.) how should we handle scenario when user searches for something but we still getting data. Easy thing to do - block controls. Other solution - update results when new data arrive.
Just for info, Is the indentation correct?
